    "narrative": "The core of today\u2019s lineup leans heavily on favorable SP matchups, with **Tyler Soderstrom** (76.91) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) anchoring the production. **Tyler Soderstrom** benefits from a massive 17% boost due to his matchup against Davis Martin, while **Mickey Moniak** maximizes his elite speed profile, capitalizing on a 14% park boost and a slow delivery from Glasnow that heavily incentivizes his stolen base potential. **Austin Riley** (72.31) also presents as a premier start, leveraging a strong 19% SP skill advantage against Taijuan Walker to maintain his status as a lineup cornerstone.\n\nThe most difficult decision for the optimizer involved **Trevor Story**, who sat at 58.15, narrowly missing the cut behind **Max Muncy** (61.91). While **Trevor Story** offered neutral platoon splits, his efficiency was capped by an elite hold-runner profile from Mize that suppressed his projected stolen base equity. We are also monitoring a 31% rain risk affecting **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Giancarlo Stanton** in their contest against Wacha; while all three remain locked in due to their high scores and favorable wind-in conditions for power suppression, we are keeping a close eye on any late-inning weather alerts.\n\nRounding out the lineup, **Corbin Carroll** (63.48) remains a high-floor start despite a challenging 19% downgrade in SP skill against Braydon Fisher. His projection holds steady due to an excellent xwOBA and a generous park factor. While we benched **James Wood** (54.26) due to the stiff challenge presented by Logan Webb, his spot at the top of the lineup remains a point of interest for future volume if he continues to see high-leverage plate appearances. We move into the slate with an aggressive stance on speed, banking on the high-efficiency matchups for **Brice Turang** and **Mickey Moniak** to keep our stolen base category competitive.",
